[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626919&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626919&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

&gt;From article &lt;1483@murtoa.cs.mu.oz.au&gt;, by kre@cs.mu.oz.au (Robert Elz):
&gt; In article &lt;MailManager.610220413.4084.mrc@Tomobiki-Cho.CAC.Washington.EDU&gt;,
&gt; mrc@TOMOBIKI-CHO.CAC.WASHINGTON.EDU (Mark Crispin) writes:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I don't think this is DEC's mistake, but rather a French mistake -- "if it
&gt;&gt; ain't &lt;mumble&gt;.FR, it ain't in France" or so they say.  I'll acknowledge that
&gt;&gt; just about every country outside the US has made this mistake too, but it
&gt;&gt; doesn't alter the fact that it's a mistake.
&gt; 
&gt; It may be a mistake, but its really not parochialism that has caused it,
&gt; but pragmatism - its the only way to stay within the rules and be part
&gt; of the domain system at the same time.
&gt; 

We are certainly not making any such mistake, but simply following MX 
records, which tells us that:

        mirsa$ nslookup
        Default Server:  mirsa
        Address:  0.0.0.0

        &gt; set type=MX
        &gt; dec.com
        Server:  mirsa
        Address:  0.0.0.0

        dec.com preference = 100, mail exchanger = decwrl.dec.com
	decwrl.dec.com  inet address = 128.45.9.1
	decwrl.dec.com  inet address = 128.45.1.1
	&gt;
DEC decided, for well understandable security reasons, that they would 
advertize only one gateway to their company network. If a shorter 
route existed, e.g. using X.400, we would indeed follow it.

To come back to the initial question on international domains, I know that
there exists at least one computer which is located in the US and named
under ".fr" (perrier.atlantic.fr). Mail from there is never stamped by the
French PTT (-).

-- Christian Huitema

